      "original_language": "Latin",
      "original": "V: Res eatenus contrariæ sunt naturæ hoc est eatenus in eodem subjecto esse nequeunt quatenus una alteram potest destruere.\n\nDEMONSTRATIO: Si enim inter se convenire vel in eodem subjecto simul esse possent, posset ergo in eodem subjecto aliquid dari quod ipsum posset destruere, quod (per propositionem præcedentem) est absurdum. Ergo res etc. Q.E.D.",
      "translation": "Things are naturally contrary, that is, cannot exist in the same object, in so far as one is capable of destroying the other.\n\nProof. — If they could agree together or co-exist in the same object, there would then be in the said object something which could destroy it; but this, by the foregoing proposition, is absurd, therefore things, &c. Q.E.D."
    },
