      "translation": "Derision is pleasure arising from our conceiving the presence of a quality, which we despise, in an object which we hate.\n\nExplanation –In so far as we despise a thing which we hate, we deny existence thereof (III. lii. note), and to that extent rejoice (III. xx.). But since we assume that man hates that which he derides, it follows that the pleasure in question is not without alloy (cf. III. xlvii. note)."
